Exercise 1 (and Solution)

Create a program that asks the user to enter their name and their age. Print out a message addressed to them that tells them the year that they will turn 100 years old. Note: for this exercise, the expectation is that you explicitly write out the year (and therefore be out of date the next year). If you want to do this in a generic way, see exercise 39.

Extras:

Add on to the previous program by asking the user for another number and printing out that many copies of the previous message. (Hint: order of operations exists in Python)
Print out that many copies of the previous message on separate lines. (Hint: the string "\n is the same as pressing the ENTER button)

name = input("Hey! your name please? ")
print("name: "+name)
age = int(input("How old are you? "))
print(f"Age of {name} is {age} old")
curr_year = 2026
later_year = curr_year-age+100
print(f"In year {later_year} you will be 100!")

while True:
    print("Know what more ages it will be 100 years? enter 'y' to continue and 'n' to exit")
    if input() == "y":
        new_age = int(input("How many more ages you want to know? "))
        later_year = curr_year-new_age+100
        print(f"In year {later_year} you will be 100!")
    else:
        print("Good bye!")
        break
